"""
MKT Christ Commentary — 2 Corinthians chapters 11-13
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-2corinthians-11-13.py

Key Christological decisions for chs 11-13:
- The Fool's Speech (11:1-12:13) is Christologically shaped: Christ himself
  was crucified in weakness (13:4), so the apostle's pattern of weakness
  mirrors the Lord's own self-emptying (Phil 2:5-11).
- The super-apostles preach 'a different Jesus' (11:4) — the Christological
  standard is the crucified-and-risen Lord, not a powerful wonder-worker.
- Satan masquerades as an angel of light (11:14) — inversion of the genuine
  light of the gospel of Christ's glory (4:4-6).
- The third-heaven ascent (12:1-4) leads to the thorn — the pattern of
  revelation followed by humbling mirrors the Christ-pattern of Phil 2:6-8:
  height followed by lowering.
- 12:9: Christ's direct speech — 'my power is made perfect in weakness' —
  already present; skipped.
- 13:3-4: Christ not weak but powerful; crucified in weakness yet lives by
  God's power — the resurrection pattern applied to apostolic ministry.
- 13:14: The Trinitarian benediction structures the entire letter's theology:
  Christ's grace, God's love, Spirit's fellowship.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CHRIST = {
  "11": {
    "1": '<p>The Fool\'s Speech opening has a Christological shadow: Christ himself submitted to \'foolishness\' by the world\'s standards — the cross was foolishness to the Greeks (1 Cor 1:23). Paul\'s performance of the fool\'s boast is shaped by the pattern of the crucified Christ, whose power was displayed precisely in what appeared as weakness and folly. The request to \'bear with a little foolishness\' echoes the community\'s vocation: to receive Christ\'s wisdom in the form of apparent foolishness.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The betrothal of the community to one husband (Christ) presents Christ as the bridegroom of the new covenant people. The OT betrothal imagery (Hos 2:19-20; Isa 54:5; Ezek 16) identifies YHWH as Israel\'s husband; Paul applies this to Christ. The community is Christ\'s bride — an identity constituted by Christ\'s own claim on the community (bought with a price, 1 Cor 6:20). Paul\'s \'godly jealousy\' mirrors Christ\'s own covenant-jealousy for his people.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The fear of minds being led astray from sincere and pure devotion to Christ (<em>haplotes kai he hagnotes... eis ton Christon</em>): the telos of the apostolic community is single-hearted devotion to Christ. Eve\'s deception by the serpent is a shadow of the current danger: the super-apostles offer \'a different Jesus\' (v.4), just as the serpent offered \'different knowledge\' — a reshaping of the community\'s orientation away from the crucified-and-risen Christ.</p>',
    "4": '<p>\'A different Jesus\' (<em>allon Iesoun</em>): the most explicit Christological criterion in the letter. The Jesus the rivals preach is different from the Jesus Paul preached — presumably a powerful wonder-worker whose power validates his apostles through spectacular demonstration, without the crucifixion-and-weakness pattern. Paul\'s Jesus is defined by the cross: power in weakness, life through death, wisdom in foolishness (1 Cor 1:18-25). Any gospel that bypasses this pattern proclaims a different Christ.</p>',
    "5": '<p>Paul\'s claim not to be inferior to the super-apostles is grounded in his knowledge of Christ crucified, not in rhetorical skill. The Christ who defines authentic apostleship (1 Cor 15:3-11) is the crucified and risen Lord whose witness-pattern includes suffering. Paul\'s apostolic credentials are credentials of the genuine Christ; the rivals\' credentials belong to a different, Christ-bypassing standard.</p>',
    "6": '<p>Paul\'s knowledge (<em>gnosis</em>) contra his lack of rhetorical training: he possesses the knowledge of Christ (cf. Phil 3:8: \'the surpassing worth of knowing Christ Jesus my Lord\'). The Christ who is God\'s wisdom (1 Cor 1:30) is accessible not through Sophistic eloquence but through the proclamation of the cross. Paul\'s undisputed knowledge of Christ stands against the rivals\' impressive delivery of a different message.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The self-lowering to elevate them (<em>emauton tapeinon hina hymeis hypsothete</em>) mirrors the Christ-hymn pattern of Phil 2:6-8: Christ humbled himself so that others might be lifted up. The theological logic of apostolic free preaching is Christological: as Christ gave himself freely (Rom 8:32), Paul gives himself freely. The pattern of costly self-giving for others\' benefit is not merely Paul\'s apostolic style but his participation in Christ\'s own self-emptying mode of operation.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The language of \'robbery\' from other churches to serve Corinth echoes the sacrificial logic of the cross: Christ became poor so that others might become rich (8:9). Paul absorbed the financial cost (from Macedonian churches) to bring the gospel without charge to Corinth. The cost-bearing for others\' benefit is a structural feature of how the Christ-pattern operates in apostolic ministry.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The brothers who supplied Paul\'s need from Macedonia (Philippian support) illustrate the mutual interdependence of the body of Christ. Paul\'s refusal to burden Corinth was not superiority but apostolic service in the pattern of Christ, who came not to be served but to serve (Mark 10:45). The financial patterns of authentic apostolic ministry mirror the self-giving of Christ himself.</p>',
    "10": '<p>\'The truth of Christ is in me\' (<em>aletheia Christou en emoi</em>): Paul invokes Christ\'s own truthfulness as the ground of his oath about the boasting policy. Christ is the truth (John 14:6); the truth of Christ dwelling in Paul is the inner standard by which his apostolic conduct is measured. The boast about free preaching is not self-serving but a witness to the truthfulness of Christ operative in the apostle\'s character.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The appeal to God\'s knowledge of Paul\'s love for the Corinthians: God who knows all things (cf. 1 Cor 13:12) knows that the free-preaching policy is motivated by love, not indifference. The appeal to divine omniscience is Christologically grounded — the same Christ before whose bema all will appear (5:10) already knows the motives of Paul\'s heart. Nothing is hidden from the One who judges justly.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The strategy to cut ground from the rivals: Paul maintains his free-preaching practice so the rivals cannot equal him on his own terms. The Christological logic: the apostle\'s distinctive mode (self-giving without charge) reflects Christ\'s own distinctive mode (giving himself without price). The rivals who charge fees are operating on a different economic-theological principle — one that contradicts the grace-economy of Christ.</p>',
    "13": '<p>\'False apostles\' (<em>pseudapostoloi</em>): their falsehood is ultimately Christological — they proclaim \'a different Jesus\' (v.4) and therefore cannot be genuine apostles of the real Christ. Masquerading as apostles of Christ while preaching a different Christ is a form of identity fraud in the deepest sense: claiming to represent one who repudiates their message. The criterion of genuine apostleship is faithfulness to the crucified-and-risen Christ.</p>',
    "14": '<p>Satan as the angel of light is the anti-type of Christ as the light of the world (John 8:12; 2 Cor 4:4-6: the gospel displays the light of the glory of Christ). Where Christ genuinely is the light — and the gospel genuinely spreads the knowledge of his glory — Satan counterfeits the same appearance. The adversary\'s strategy is imitation: substituting a deceptive light for the genuine light of Christ. Discernment requires knowing the genuine Christ well enough to recognize the counterfeit.</p>',
    "15": '<p>\'Servants of righteousness\' (<em>diakonoi dikaiosyne</em>) — the rivals claim the same title that Paul uses for the new-covenant ministry (3:9: the ministry that brings righteousness). Their counterfeit righteousness-ministry echoes the adversary\'s counterfeit light. The eschatological judgment — \'their end will be what their actions deserve\' — is the bema of Christ (5:10) applied to false apostles. All will stand before the same judge.</p>',
    "16": '<p>The resumption of the fool\'s boast: Paul is about to perform in the mode of worldly boasting (<em>kata sarka</em>) while simultaneously distancing himself from it. The Christological irony: the Lord of glory, who took the form of a servant (Phil 2:7), is the one whose apostle must temporarily don the foolish form of competitive self-promotion in order to demolish it. Paul imitates the rivals\' mode to expose its emptiness, just as Christ entered the world\'s mode to redeem it from within.</p>',
    "17": '<p>\'Not as the Lord would speak\' (<em>ou kata Kyrion</em>): the disclaimer that the Fool\'s Speech is not the Lord\'s mode. The Lord\'s mode of speaking is the cross-shaped proclamation of 1 Cor 1:18-25 — not competitive credential-display. The very need for the Fool\'s Speech arises from the community\'s failure to hold to the Lord\'s standard; Paul bends temporarily to their frame to correct it.</p>',
    "18": '<p>\'Since many are boasting in the way the world does (kata sarka)...I too will boast\': Paul\'s accommodation is tactical, not principled. The flesh-standard of boasting is the criterion the super-apostles use; Paul will beat them at their own game to show the absurdity of the game itself. The Christ-standard would render all such comparison irrelevant — but the Corinthians, seduced by the flesh-standard, must be reached where they are.</p>',
    "19": '<p>The biting irony at the community\'s self-presumed wisdom. The Corinthians\' wisdom (which Paul addressed in 1 Cor 1-4 as a misidentification of divine wisdom) has not improved: they still evaluate apostolic credentials by Sophistic-worldly standards rather than by the cross\'s standard. The Christ who is the wisdom of God (1 Cor 1:30) is still being bypassed in favor of impressive human performance.</p>',
    "20": '<p>The catalogue of abuses the Corinthians tolerate from the rivals — enslaving, devouring, taking advantage of, putting on airs, slapping in the face — is the antithesis of Christ\'s mode of apostolic service. Christ came not to be served but to serve and give his life (Mark 10:45); the rivals\' dominance of the community is the inversion of Christ\'s servant-form. The Corinthians\' tolerance of domination reveals how far they are from Christ\'s pattern of self-giving leadership.</p>',
    "21": '<p>\'To my shame I admit we were too weak for that!\': the irony reaches its climax. Paul\'s gentleness and non-exploitation appear as \'weakness\' precisely because they reflect Christ\'s own kenosis (self-emptying). The rivals\' domination is \'strength\' by the flesh-standard; Paul\'s service is \'weakness.\' But the Christ-standard reverses the evaluation completely: Christ\'s weakness on the cross is the ultimate strength (1 Cor 1:25).</p>',
    "22": '<p>Are they Hebrews? Israelites? Abraham\'s descendants? Paul matches each claim. The ethnic-religious credentials being cited by the rivals are evaluated by a standard — fleshly descent and national identity — that Paul radically relativized in Phil 3:2-8: these were \'gains\' he counts as loss for the sake of knowing Christ. The rivals\' Christless boasting in Abrahamic descent echoes the Judaizers; Paul concedes the ethnic credentials while insisting on the Christological criterion.</p>',
    "23": '<p>\'Servants of Christ\' (<em>diakonoi Christou</em>) — now the Christological comparison proper. Paul claims to be more. The peristasis catalogue that follows (vv. 23-33) is his evidence. The marks of a genuine servant of Christ are not rhetorical displays or social credentials but the pattern of suffering that mirrors Christ\'s own path: \'I have been in prison more frequently, been flogged more severely, been exposed to death again and again.\' The servant\'s path follows the Lord\'s path.</p>',
    "24": '<p>Five synagogue floggings, each thirty-nine lashes: Paul\'s repeated subjection to Jewish communal discipline indicates his sustained involvement with synagogue communities throughout his missionary career. The floggings are marks of identification with Christ who was also beaten and condemned by both Jewish and Roman authorities. The apostle\'s body carries the marks of the same rejected-and-condemned pattern that Christ\'s body bore.</p>',
    "25": '<p>Three Roman beatings with rods, one stoning, three shipwrecks: each episode is a specific instantiation of the dying-of-Jesus carried in the body (4:10). The stoning at Lystra (Acts 14:19), the beatings, the shipwrecks — all are moments when death was at work in Paul so that life might work in the communities (4:12). The historical specificity of the catalogue makes it undeniable: this apostle\'s body has actually borne the suffering that shapes genuine Christ-conformity.</p>',
    "26": '<p>The geography of danger — rivers, bandits, fellow Jews, Gentiles, city, wilderness, sea, false brothers — maps the comprehensiveness of apostolic exposure. The risen Christ who sent Paul (Acts 9:15-16: \'I will show him how much he must suffer for my name\') foreknew and commissioned this very pattern of suffering. Paul\'s hardships are not accidents but the appointed shape of his Christ-conforming ministry.</p>',
    "27": '<p>Labor, toil, sleeplessness, hunger, thirst, cold, nakedness: the physical dimensions of Christ-conforming apostolic service. The self-expenditure of 12:15 (\'spend and be entirely spent\') is not rhetorical — these are the literal costs. Paul\'s body is being consumed in the service of the communities, replicating the logic of Christ\'s own body given for others (1 Cor 11:24: \'this is my body, which is for you\').</p>',
    "28": '<p>\'The daily pressure of concern for all the churches\' (<em>merimna pason ton ekklesion</em>): Paul\'s pastoral anxiety is the interior dimension of his apostolic suffering. As Christ intercedes for his people (Rom 8:34; Heb 7:25), Paul carries pastoral concern that never ceases. The apostle\'s interior life mirrors the Lord\'s: a persistent, compassionate concern for the community\'s welfare that refuses to be relieved by distance or difficulty.</p>',
    "29": '<p>\'Who is weak, and I do not feel weak?\' — Paul\'s empathetic identification with the community\'s weakness is the apostolic form of Christ\'s own high-priestly sympathy: \'we do not have a high priest who is unable to sympathize with our weaknesses\' (Heb 4:15). Paul\'s sharing in the community\'s weakness is a Christological participation — the same solidarity that Christ exercises from the heavenly throne, Paul exercises through apostolic pastoral presence.</p>',
    "30": '<p>\'If I must boast, I will boast of the things that show my weakness\': the Christological reversal of the boasting-standard. Christ\'s cross was the ultimate display of weakness — and the ultimate display of God\'s power. Paul\'s boasting in weakness is the apostolic participation in the same cross-logic: \'the message of the cross is foolishness to those who are perishing, but to us who are being saved it is the power of God\' (1 Cor 1:18). Boasting in weakness is boasting in Christ crucified.</p>',
    "31": '<p>The oath before \'the God and Father of the Lord Jesus, who is to be praised forever\': the doxological formula identifies God by his relationship to Jesus — not as creator or lawgiver in the abstract but as \'the Father of the Lord Jesus Christ.\' This Christological identification of God is characteristic of Paul throughout (1:3; Rom 15:6; Eph 1:3). God is known and praised in relation to Christ; the doxology is always Christologically shaped.</p>',
    "32": '<p>The Damascus escape under Aretas IV: the historical anchor of Paul\'s post-conversion life. The Damascus of Paul\'s conversion (Acts 9:1-25) was the site of his first encounter with the risen Christ (Acts 9:3-6) and his first near-death escape. The entire trajectory of Paul\'s missionary career — from Damascus flight to this letter written from Macedonia — flows from that original encounter with the Christ who appeared to him and said \'I am Jesus whom you are persecuting\' (Acts 9:5).</p>',
    "33": '<p>Lowered in a basket to escape: the inglorious exit that closes the Fool\'s Speech. The apostle of the risen Lord, who could have boasted of his Damascus-road encounter with the glorified Christ, instead narrates his escape in a produce-basket. The anti-triumphal image is deliberately Christological: the Lord who was laid in a manger, who entered Jerusalem on a donkey, who was buried in a borrowed tomb, is represented by an apostle who escapes in a basket. Apostolic glory is hidden under the form of apparent shame.</p>'
  },
  "12": {
    "1": '<p>The heavenly ascent Paul reluctantly narrates is placed in the context of the Fool\'s Speech — he has \'nothing to gain\' by narrating it. This reluctance itself is Christological: the Christ who did not grasp equality with God (Phil 2:6) did not exploit his divine status for public display. Paul\'s reticence about the ascent experience mirrors the Lord\'s own pattern of power concealed rather than displayed. The genuine apostle of Christ does not leverage spiritual experiences as credentials.</p>',
    "2": '<p>Already present — skipping.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The repeated agnosticism about the body/soul state during the ascent (\'whether in the body or apart from the body I do not know\') is Christologically significant: the risen Christ himself transcends the ordinary body/soul distinction — his resurrection body is both the same as and transformed from the body that was crucified. Paul\'s uncertainty about his own state during the ascent reflects his encounter with the sphere of eschatological existence that Christ already inhabits.</p>',
    "4": '<p>\'Caught up to paradise and heard inexpressible things\' (<em>arreta rhemata</em>): the things not to be spoken stand in contrast to Christ\'s own revelation, which is meant to be proclaimed. The gospel of the crucified Christ is the \'open secret\' (compare the Markan messianic secret, where the hidden identity is finally proclaimed at the cross). The inexpressible heavenly revelations are subordinate to the publicly proclaimed Christ; Paul\'s experience of the heavenly realm does not displace the cross as the center of his message.</p>',
    "5": '<p>\'I will boast about that person, but not about myself, except about my weaknesses\': the deliberate self-distancing from the ascent-experience is the Christ-pattern applied. Christ, though equal with God, \'made himself nothing, taking the very nature of a servant\' (Phil 2:7) — he distanced himself from the display of his divine status. Paul similarly refuses to leverage the heavenly vision for apostolic credential-building. The pattern of concealment and voluntary limitation mirrors Christ\'s own kenosis.</p>',
    "6": '<p>\'So no one will think more of me than what they observe or hear from me\': Paul grounds apostolic evaluation in observable conduct and audible proclamation — the body of Christ visible in suffering, the word of Christ audible in preaching. This is the epistemology of the incarnation: the eternal Son made himself available to human observation and hearing (1 John 1:1-3: what we have seen, heard, and touched). Paul\'s apostolic presentation follows the same mode of humble visibility.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The thorn in the flesh as \'a messenger of Satan\' (<em>angelos Satana</em>): even the adversary\'s instrument serves God\'s purpose — to prevent Paul from becoming conceited about the surpassing revelations. The same sovereign God who allowed the adversary to test Job (Job 1:12) permits the thorn to keep Paul in the weakness-pattern. The suffering is allowed \'because of these surpassingly great revelations\' — the greater the Christological privilege, the deeper the corresponding humbling. Cf. Phil 2:9: the exaltation comes after the humbling, not before.</p>',
    "8": '<p>Three petitions for the thorn\'s removal mirror Gethsemane\'s three-fold prayer (Matt 26:39-44: \'let this cup pass\' — prayed three times, denied three times). Both prayers are answered with divine presence and sufficient grace rather than removal. The pattern establishes that Christ himself was not exempt from unanswered petition — the cup was not removed, and the cross followed. Paul\'s unanswered petition for relief connects his experience to the Lord\'s own experience of the Father\'s \'no\' to escape.</p>',
    "10": '<p>\'Delight in weaknesses, insults, hardships, persecutions, difficulties for Christ\'s sake\' (<em>hyper Christou</em>): the suffering is explicitly for Christ — conformity to Christ is the category that transforms the hardship-list from complaint to boast. \'For when I am weak, then I am strong\' (<em>hotan gar asthenoo, tote dynatos eimi</em>): the resurrection-logic applied to present experience. As Christ\'s weakness on the cross was the locus of God\'s ultimate power (13:4), Paul\'s weakness is the locus of Christ\'s power now (12:9).</p>',
    "11": '<p>\'I ought to have been commended by you, for I am not inferior to the super-apostles, even though I am nothing\': the paradox of apostolic identity — superior to the rivals in the genuine apostolic standard and simultaneously \'nothing\' (<em>ouden eimi</em>). Paul echoes 1 Cor 15:9-10: \'I am the least of the apostles... but by the grace of God I am what I am.\' The criterion is always external to Paul — Christ and his grace — not Paul\'s own achievement.</p>',
    "12": '<p>\'The marks of a true apostle\' (<em>semeia tou apostolou</em>) — signs, wonders, miracles — performed among them. Paul does not deny the validity of miraculous authentication, but the signs are performed \'with great perseverance\' (<em>en pase hypomone</em>). The context of miraculous signs is patient endurance — the cross-pattern holds even in the midst of power. The Christ who performed signs throughout his ministry always moved toward the cross; authentic sign-performing apostleship is similarly cross-shaped.</p>',
    "13": '<p>The ironic apology for never burdening them financially. Paul\'s non-exploitation policy is his distinguishing mark as a genuine servant of Christ — the one who \'though he was rich, yet for your sake he became poor\' (8:9). The rivals who accept payment are implicitly identified as contradicting the Christ-pattern of voluntary impoverishment for others\' enrichment. The \'wrong\' Paul sarcastically apologizes for is actually his most Christological act.</p>',
    "14": '<p>\'What I want is not your possessions but you\' (<em>ou gar zetoo ta hymon alla hymas</em>): Paul seeks persons, not resources. This is the Christ-pattern: Christ sought the lost sheep itself (Luke 15:4-7), not the sheep\'s wool. The parental metaphor — parents save up for children — frames the apostolic relationship in terms of the self-giving love that characterizes God\'s relationship to his people. Paul is the father-representative who spends on the community as God spends on his children.</p>',
    "15": '<p>\'I will very gladly spend and be entirely spent (<em>ekdapanethisomai</em>) for your lives\': the complete self-expenditure for the community replicates the logic of Christ\'s death — given entirely for others. \'For you\' (<em>hyper hymon</em>): the same preposition Paul uses for Christ\'s death throughout (5:14-15: \'one died for all\'; 8:9: \'became poor for your sake\'). The apostle\'s self-expenditure is a participation in and extension of Christ\'s own \'for you\'.</p>',
    "16": '<p>The accusation of trickery (<em>doloo</em>): Paul is accused of the very cunning he attributed to the serpent (11:3: <em>panourgia</em>). The inversion is sharp — Paul\'s Christological openness (4:2: \'by the open display of truth\') is accused of concealed manipulation. The charge is refuted by the pattern of conduct: an apostle who operates in Christ\'s mode (transparent, free-giving, non-exploitative) cannot simultaneously be deceiving through agents.</p>',
    "17": '<p>The conduct of Titus and the anonymous brother as evidence of apostolic integrity: the community of co-workers who walk in the same footsteps reflects the body-of-Christ principle — Christ\'s character is expressed consistently through all genuine members of his apostolic community. The consistency across multiple persons is evidence that the conduct flows from a common Christological source, not from individual calculation.</p>',
    "18": '<p>\'Did we not walk in the same footsteps?\' (<em>tois autois ichnesin</em>): the footstep-metaphor recalls following in Christ\'s steps (1 Pet 2:21: \'Christ suffered for you, leaving you an example, that you should follow in his steps\'). Paul and Titus walk the same path because both follow the same Christ. Apostolic consistency of conduct across persons and situations is the corporate expression of Christ-conformity in action.</p>',
    "19": '<p>\'We have been speaking in the sight of God as those in Christ\' (<em>en Christo laloumen</em>): the entire Fool\'s Speech — the paradoxical boasting in weakness, the defense, the irony — has been spoken \'in Christ,\' under Christ\'s Lordship, for the community\'s building up. The phrase \'in Christ\' is Paul\'s fundamental location-of-existence (2 Cor 5:17: \'if anyone is in Christ, the new creation has come\'). Even the most uncomfortable apostolic communication happens within that Christological sphere.</p>',
    "20": '<p>The vice catalogue that Paul fears finding: quarreling, jealousy, anger, factionalism, slander, gossip, arrogance, disorder — all are contraventions of Christ\'s self-giving love. The community shaped by \'a different Jesus\' (11:4) produces the divisive behaviors of worldly competition rather than the unity of the body of Christ. The feared disorder is the consequence of Christological deficiency — a community that has lost the crucified Christ as its center reverts to the status-competition of the surrounding culture.</p>',
    "21": '<p>Paul\'s fear of being humbled before them by God (<em>tapeinosei me ho theos</em>): the humbling-verb (<em>tapeinoo</em>) is the verb of Christ\'s kenosis in Phil 2:8 (\'he humbled himself and became obedient to death\'). Paul participates in the same humbling pattern: his apostolic authority cannot override the community\'s failure to repent, just as Christ\'s divine authority submitted to the human response. The grief over unrepentant members is the pastoral form of Christ\'s own grief over Jerusalem (Matt 23:37).</p>'
  },
  "13": {
    "1": '<p>\'Every charge must be established by the testimony of two or three witnesses\' (Deut 17:6; 19:15): Paul applies the Mosaic legal standard to the third visit, framing it as a formal apostolic proceeding. The legal framework is Christologically significant: Jesus himself appealed to the two-witness principle in John 8:17-18, offering his own testimony and the Father\'s as the required two witnesses. Paul stands in the stream of this Christological application of Mosaic legal categories.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The warning to those who sinned earlier and to all others: Paul\'s authority is exercised as Christ\'s ambassador (5:20), and his coming visit carries the weight of Christ\'s own authority over the community. The \'I will not spare\' (<em>ou pheisomai</em>) echoes God\'s own warnings throughout the OT (cf. Ezek 5:11). The apostle\'s discipline is not personal vengeance but the exercise of Christ\'s own lordship over his community through the apostolic office.</p>',
    "3": '<p>\'Since you are demanding proof that Christ speaks through me\': the ultimate apostolic question. Paul\'s entire letter has been the evidence — but the Christological criterion for apostolicity is finally stated here: Christ speaks through Paul. The Christ who speaks is \'not weak in dealing with you but is powerful among you\' (<em>ou asthenei eis hymas alla dynatei en hymin</em>). This is the risen, powerful Christ — present and active in the community that came into existence through Paul\'s preaching.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A direct revelation of the Christ-pattern: \'he was crucified in weakness (<em>ex astheneias</em>), yet he lives by the power of God (<em>ek dynameoas theou</em>).\' The past crucifixion in weakness and the present life in God\'s power define the entire Christological structure of the letter: 4:10 (carrying the death of Jesus so his life may be manifested), 5:14-15 (one died for all so that the living might live for him), 12:9 (power made perfect in weakness). Paul and his co-workers are \'weak in him\' (<em>asthenoumen en auto</em>) but \'will live with him\' (<em>zesomen syn auto</em>) by God\'s power in dealing with the Corinthians — the resurrection-pattern operative in the apostolic community.</p>',
    "5": '<p>\'Examine yourselves to see whether you are in the faith. Test yourselves. Do you not realize that Jesus Christ is in you?\' (<em>Iesous Christos en hymin estin</em>): the community\'s inner test is the presence of Christ within them. The indwelling Christ (cf. Gal 2:20: \'it is no longer I who live, but Christ who lives in me\'; Col 1:27: \'Christ in you, the hope of glory\') is both the criterion and the evidence of genuine faith. The self-examination invited here is not introspection for its own sake but orientation toward the Christ who indwells.</p>',
    "6": '<p>\'I hope you will discover that we have not failed the test\' (<em>ouk esmen adokimoi</em>): Paul\'s apostolic credentialing is bound to the community\'s spiritual life. If Christ is genuinely in them, he got there through Paul\'s gospel. The self-examination of the community is simultaneously the vindication of Paul\'s ministry — not because Paul needs vindication for personal reasons, but because the community\'s Christ-life is the evidence of the gospel\'s genuine operation through Paul.</p>',
    "7": '<p>Paul\'s prayer: that the community would do what is right, even if it makes Paul appear to have failed the test. The Christological precedent: Christ himself \'appeared\' to have failed — condemned, crucified, abandoned — yet this was the moment of God\'s ultimate vindication. Paul\'s willingness to appear powerless (if no discipline is needed) reflects the same Christ-pattern: the apparent weakness of unenforced authority is acceptable when the community\'s good is served.</p>',
    "8": '<p>\'We cannot work against the truth, only for it\' (<em>ou gar dynametha ti kata tes aletheias alla hyper tes aletheias</em>): the truth is Christ himself (John 14:6). Apostolic authority can only work in alignment with Christ\'s own direction — the apostle cannot exercise power contrary to the one in whose name the authority is given. Truth is not an abstract principle but the person of Christ, whose character and mission define the limits and direction of all genuine apostolic activity.</p>',
    "9": '<p>\'We are glad whenever we are weak and you are strong\': the apostolic joy in the community\'s strength mirrors Christ\'s own purpose — not to establish apostolic dominance but to build up the community. The prayer for \'your complete restoration\' (<em>hymon katartisin</em>) is the prayer of Christ for his people: the interceding Christ (Rom 8:34; Heb 7:25) seeks the community\'s wholeness and completion. Paul\'s prayer participates in Christ\'s own intercessory work.</p>',
    "10": '<p>Authority given by the Lord for building up, not tearing down (<em>oikodomein eis oikodomen kai ouk eis kathairesen</em>): the telos of all Christological authority is construction of the community. Christ himself came to build his church (Matt 16:18), not to condemn the world but to save it (John 3:17). The apostle\'s authority is a delegated share in Christ\'s own constructive purpose; its exercise against the community would contradict the commission from which it is derived.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The closing exhortations — restoration, encouragement, one mind, peace — describe the community\'s life in Christ. \'The God of love and peace will be with you\': the God characterized by love (<em>agape</em>) and peace (<em>eirene</em>) is the God revealed in Christ (5:19: God was in Christ reconciling; Rom 5:1: we have peace with God through our Lord Jesus Christ). The promise of God\'s presence with the community is the Immanuel-promise fulfilled in Christ (Matt 1:23; 28:20: I am with you always).</p>',
    "12": '<p>The holy kiss as the community\'s embodied greeting: the physical gesture of fictive kinship enacted among those who are united in Christ. The community constituted by Christ\'s body-and-blood (1 Cor 10:16-17; 11:23-26) expresses that constitutive union in mutual physical greeting. The holy kiss is a sacramental gesture — a bodily sign of the spiritual reality of belonging to one another in Christ.</p>',
    "13": '<p>All the saints with Paul send greetings: the wider body of Christ participating in the letter\'s closing. The apostolic community is not a solitary enterprise but the body of Christ spread across multiple communities, all united in the one Lord. The co-greeting witnesses to the catholicity of the church: the Christ who is one (1 Cor 8:6; Eph 4:5) creates one body that greets itself across geographical distance.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A direct revelation structured as a Trinitarian benediction: \'the grace of the Lord Jesus Christ, the love of God, and the fellowship of the Holy Spirit be with you all.\' The three-person structure names the full triune God as the source of the community\'s life: Christ\'s grace (the gift of his saving work), God\'s love (the Father\'s eternal love expressed in giving the Son, John 3:16; Rom 5:8), and the Spirit\'s fellowship (<em>koinonia</em> — the participation in the divine life that the Spirit mediates, Phil 2:1). The community\'s existence is grounded in and sustained by the full triune God whose self-giving is the structure of all reality.</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', '2corinthians')
    merge_comm(existing, CHRIST)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', '2corinthians', existing)
    for ch in ['11', '12', '13']:
        count = len(existing.get(ch, {}))
        print(f'  ch{ch}: {count} entries')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
